I am using the Java API to formulate a MaxSAT problem. The problem contains some assertions of the form `(=> a (xor b (xor c (xor d ...))))` where all variables in the assertion are booleans (defined using `mkBoolConst`). An example is [formulation.txt](https://github.com/Z3Prover/z3/files/1229426/formulation.txt); I apologize for the length of the example.

I create the `Optimize` object as follows:
```java
Map<String, String> z3Config = new LinkedHashMap<String, String>();
z3Config.put("model", "true");
Context ctx = new Context(z3Config);
Optimize solver = ctx.mkOptimize();
```

I get the values of the desired boolean variables as follows:
```java
solver.Check();
solver.getModel().getConstInterp(...);
```

When obtaining the solution using the Java API, I get a solution that violates some of the assertions of the aforementioned form that appear in lines 4393 through 7312 of the example. However, if I save the output of `solver.toString()` to a file and run Z3 on the command line, then I get a valid solution.

I am using the latest version of `master` (commit `97e263`). 

This issue may be related to #1112. I tried to load in my saved file to see if I could reproduce the same behavior described in that issue:
```java
Map<String, String> z3Config = new LinkedHashMap<String, String>();
z3Config.put("model", "true");
Context newContext = new Context(z3Config);
Optimize newSolver = ctx.mkOptimize();
			
String code = FileUtils.readFileToString(new File("/tmp/formulation.z3"), Charset.defaultCharset());
BoolExpr assertions = newContext.parseSMTLIB2String(code, null, null, null, null);
newSolver.Add(assertions);
```
However, I get errors that assert-soft is unsupported.

I am happy to run more experiments or provide other output/code if it's useful. Just let me know what I should provide.

